00:57:24.239 --> 00:57:29.600
makes some people dive deep too quickly without seeing the big picture in the visualization.

00:57:30.320 --> 00:57:34.560
Do you have a way of thinking about when tool tips or a table view are useful

00:57:35.520 --> 00:57:42.719
and when they're distracting? Yeah, that's always the, a lot of the times I go, we should,

00:57:42.719 --> 00:57:46.479
but we shouldn't. And I fight myself into a circle. And then at the end of the day,

00:57:47.360 --> 00:57:50.719
the highest title in the room is the one that decides whether or not we have them.

00:57:51.280 --> 00:57:56.639
If the CEO wants all of them, they're going in. I spend some time maybe designing that tool tip

00:57:56.639 --> 00:58:02.080
so that it's less intrusive or it's easier to scan. And again, in product design world,

00:58:02.399 --> 00:58:07.120
there's lots of talk about how the nutrient label on food, how scannable is that? How does that,

00:58:07.120 --> 00:58:12.159
that's a tool tip on a physical product, right? So I spend some time designing how that tool tip

00:58:12.159 --> 00:58:19.040
might pop up. But if the CEO wants it, it's happening. If a low level analyst wants it,

00:58:19.040 --> 00:58:22.959
or not a low level, but down the chain analyst, and this is being delivered to everybody,

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:29.520
maybe I turn it off for everybody, but offer a packaged version to that analyst who really wants

00:58:29.520 --> 00:58:35.439
to do some exploration. If I can get the space on all of our servers, I'll have two versions of

00:58:35.439 --> 00:58:42.719
that dashboard, the executive version and the analyst version. And so sometimes the CEO wants,

00:58:42.719 --> 00:58:46.320
this is what you get shared at, unless you ask too many questions, then we give you this one,

00:58:46.320 --> 00:58:52.080
which hopefully spurs more questions. So it almost ends up as the highest title in the room.

00:58:52.080 --> 00:58:59.120
And then if I have fellow curious data people that I try and serve them because they're trying

00:58:59.120 --> 00:59:05.919
to answer questions too, or find more questions. So kind of a wishy-washy answer on that one, but

00:59:05.919 --> 00:59:11.919
sometimes that's what it is. Thank you so much, Laura. As we get to the end here,

00:59:11.919 --> 00:59:15.919
I'm just wondering if people want to connect with you, what's the best way? Is it LinkedIn

00:59:15.919 --> 00:59:21.439
or through your blog? Yeah, LinkedIn or I'm on threads, but my threads is kind of

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:28.080
not professional, but I feel like this is not professional. It's just fun nerds making jokes

00:59:28.080 --> 00:59:33.600
about bad product design. So LinkedIn is the best, the easiest place in a professional capacity.

00:59:34.879 --> 00:59:40.560
Awesome. I did just want to share, we do have a data science hangout community LinkedIn group,

00:59:40.560 --> 00:59:45.600
maybe sometimes not the best way to have back and forth conversation, but we try sometimes,

00:59:45.600 --> 00:59:50.959
but I shared it in the chat there. If anybody wants to join that group to make it easier to

00:59:50.959 --> 00:59:56.479
connect with each other as well. I love getting to hear about people who are friends now because

00:59:56.479 --> 01:00:01.280
they met in the data science hangout or maybe met each other in the chat, sharing resources.

01:00:02.159 --> 01:00:07.360
But thank you so much, Laura, for joining us today and sharing your experience. This has

01:00:07.360 --> 01:00:11.600
been so fun. Absolutely. Thank you, everyone. And I'm very open to questions on LinkedIn,

01:00:11.600 --> 01:00:17.199
just send me questions. Awesome. Well, thank you all. Have a great rest of the day.

01:00:17.199 --> 01:00:19.919
So nice to see you. Bye everyone. Bye.

01:00:26.479 --> 01:00:26.979
Bye.

